title: Insects and other Arthropods of Mt Macedon
description:
Arthropod species found at Mount Macedon and nearby areas.
Includes all arthropods: (insects, arachnids, crustaceans and myriapods).

items.title: Antimerus smaragdinus
items.content_text:
One of the Rove Beetles which have short elytra leaving most of the abdomen exposed. Full-sized wings are folded up under the elytra.
"Head, pronotum and elytra generally with metallic green or blue reflection; elytral surface between punctures very finely pitted; abdominal terga with vague elevation along midline (Distribution: southern New South Wales, Victoria, South Australia, Tasmania)"
First record for the Macedon Ranges.
Thanks to Nick Porch for the identification.

items.title: Nemophora topazias
items.content_text:
A Fairy Moth. Note the super-long antennae. Size - very small, body about 8 mm long.
Thanks to Tony D., Ken W., Russell B. and Axel K. for help with the identification.
Update from Axel: "It is Nemophora topazias, not sparsella! It is a species from Acacia that seems to be more often seen in autumn. N. sparsella does not have the yellow basal spot, feeds on Bursaria and flies in early summer."

items.content_text: Possibly a Snipe Fly. Chrysopilus sp. (Rhagionidae)

items.title: Coccinella transversalis
items.content_text: Ladybird larva about 7mm long. Predatory- (chasing Drosophila flies in my compost bin)

items.title: Drosophila (Drosophila) spp.
items.content_text: Vinegar fly. Swarms around decaying fruit in my compost bin

items.title: Vanessa kershawi
items.content_text: Vanessa kershawi on Grasstree

items.title: Acanthosomatidae spp., Stauralia spp.
items.content_text: "Parent bug" on Pimelea humilis flowers. I think it belongs to the genus Stauralia.

items.title: Amegilla chlorocyanea
items.content_text:
Common Blue-banded Bee visiting the potted Trigger-plants in my greenhouse.
Scroll down to 2nd photo to see action shot. Note resulting dusting of pollen in first shot.

items.title: Agrotis infusa
items.content_text: Swarming at Mt Macedon. Hiding in crevices.

items.title: Leptomyrmex erythrocephalus
items.content_text: Our resident Spider-ant. Lives under our concrete verandah. In these photos it was breaking up and carrying off pieces of sausage meat. There must be more than one ant in the colony but we only see one at a time.

items.title: Acarina spp., Chauliognathus lugubris
items.content_text:
Red mites on Plague Soldier Beetles.
The mites are at the larval stage with 6 long hairy legs instead of 8 legs as in the adult.

items.title: Cercopoidea spp.
items.content_text:
Froghoppers or "Spittle Bugs" (Cercopidae: Cercopinae) on Acacia mearnsii.
I suspect that the adult shown has just emerged from its moult and is not showing its final darker colouration.
http://www1.dpi.nsw.gov.au/keys/cercopid/cercopid/index.html

items.title: Parepisparis lutosaria
items.content_text: Moth on my kitchen window. Possibly Parepisparis lutosaria. Wingspan about 3.5 cm

items.title: Hippotion scrofa
items.content_text: Hawk Moth clinging to a Hairy-leaf Stylidium in my greenhouse.

items.title: Eurema smilax smilax
items.content_text: Feeding on Westringia fruticosa var. in garden.

items.title: Papilio aegeus aegeus
items.content_text:
Resting on a banksia rose and drinking from wet ground. (Same individual)
Host plant (lemon tree)nearby in my backyard.

items.title: Papilio aegeus aegeus
items.content_text: On a Philotheca myoporoides plant.Showing the everted two-pronged red osmeterium which is normally hidden but is everted when the caterpillar is disturbed.The osmeterium emits a foul-smelling secretion.
